('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:exam:95892d41', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "Which one of the following actions should the car dealership take to help increase its sales during a period of falling consumer income?", "options": ["A — Advertise less", "B — Offer price reductions", "C — Reduce customer engagement", "D — Reduce its costs"], "caseStudy": "Falling levels of consumer income have caused a car dealership to experience a significant reduction in retail sales.", "hint": "Think about what happens when customers have less money. What marketing action directly makes products more affordable and attractive to price-sensitive buyers?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n  <h5>Answer: B — Offer price reductions</h5>\n  <p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> When consumer incomes fall, customers have less money to spend. Offering price reductions makes the cars more accessible to buyers with reduced budgets, directly addressing the affordability problem and helping to maintain demand.</p>\n  <br>\n  <p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>A — Advertise less:</strong> Reducing advertising would make the business less visible to potential customers, likely causing sales to fall further — the opposite of what is needed.</li>\n    <li><strong>C — Reduce customer engagement:</strong> Poor customer engagement means fewer interactions with potential buyers, reducing the chance of making a sale. This would worsen the problem.</li>\n    <li><strong>D — Reduce its costs:</strong> While reducing costs is a sensible internal strategy during a downturn, it does not directly increase sales. The question asks what should be done to increase sales, not to manage internal finances.</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "B — Offer price reductions."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:exam:67a58fa2', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Textbook Q1 (Knowledge)", "question": "Which of the following statements is true?", "options": ["A — The sales of a business will always increase when incomes rise", "B — Rising incomes often lead to an increase in the sales of luxury goods", "C — A rise in unemployment will make all consumers worse off", "D — A fall in consumer income will always cause a business to sell less"], "caseStudy": "JC Motors Ltd have been trading for 20 years. They specialise in selling high-end bespoke cars that start from £50,000 and can be as expensive as £300,000. Owing to the recent downturn in the economy that has led to falling consumer incomes and an increase in unemployment from 2 million to 2.2 million people, they have started to diversify and have a small range of second hand cars on sale that start at £15,000 and go up to £80,000.", "hint": "Watch out for the words ''always'' and ''all'' — these are clues that a statement is likely to be FALSE. Think about which statement is sometimes true and not an absolute rule.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n  <h5>Answer: B — Rising incomes often lead to an increase in the sales of luxury goods</h5>\n  <p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> When incomes rise, customers can afford higher-quality and non-essential items. Luxury goods businesses like JC Motors typically benefit from rising incomes, as more customers can consider purchasing high-end products. The word ''often'' makes this statement accurate — it is a tendency, not an absolute rule.</p>\n  <br>\n  <p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>A — \"Will always increase\":</strong> FALSE. Businesses selling cheap or budget goods may actually see sales FALL when incomes rise, as customers trade up to more expensive alternatives.</li>\n    <li><strong>C — \"Will make ALL consumers worse off\":</strong> FALSE. Not all consumers are unemployed. Those who keep their jobs may even benefit if lower unemployment causes wages to eventually rise. Budget shoppers may also find it easier to get work.</li>\n    <li><strong>D — \"Will always cause a business to sell less\":</strong> FALSE. Discount retailers like Aldi can see sales RISE when consumer incomes fall, as customers switch to cheaper options.</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "B — Rising incomes often lead to an increase in the sales of luxury goods."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:c09f5a6d', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does the term ''economic climate'' refer to?", "options": ["The weather conditions affecting a country''s agriculture", "How well the country is doing in terms of income and employment levels", "The level of inflation in the economy", "The number of businesses trading in a country"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: The economic climate refers to how well the country is doing in terms of the levels of income and employment. It does NOT refer to weather or climate change — a common examiner-noted mistake."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:85d099c0', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Consumer spending is most likely to fall when:", "options": ["Average incomes rise", "Unemployment falls", "The country produces less as measured by GDP", "Immigration rises"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: When GDP falls (a recession), incomes and employment also fall, reducing consumer spending. Rising incomes (A) and falling unemployment (B) both increase spending. Immigration (D) is not directly linked."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:9cb53c21', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "In a period of rising income and employment, most businesses can expect:", "options": ["Prices to fall", "Sales to rise", "Profits to fall", "Immigration to fall"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: When incomes rise, customers have more to spend, so demand increases and sales rise. Prices typically rise (not fall) in a growing economy, and profits usually increase too."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:d8daed93', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "When a business loses sales due to a fall in consumer income, it should:", "options": ["Increase the amount it produces", "Stop selling the product abroad", "Reduce production costs", "Recruit more workers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: Reducing production costs allows the business to lower prices or maintain profit margins despite falling sales. Increasing production (A) or recruiting more workers (D) would be counterproductive when demand is falling."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:d8a4189c', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A tour company has average annual sales of £8 million. When income falls by 2%, its sales fall by 4%. What is the expected fall in sales if income fell by 2%?", "options": ["£80,000", "£160,000", "£320,000", "£640,000"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: A 4% fall on £8 million = £8,000,000 × 0.04 = £320,000. Option A (£80,000) is 1% of £8m. Option B (£160,000) is 2% of £8m. Option D (£640,000) is 8% of £8m."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:dadc7cac', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is most likely to benefit from a fall in consumer incomes?", "options": ["A luxury car dealership", "A five-star hotel chain", "A budget supermarket selling own-label products", "A high-end bespoke kitchen manufacturer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: When incomes fall, consumers trade down to cheaper alternatives, benefiting discount retailers. Luxury and high-end businesses (A, B, D) suffer as consumers can no longer afford their products."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:bee293f6', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the most likely impact of falling unemployment on a business''s production costs?", "options": ["Costs will fall because there are fewer workers to pay", "Costs will rise because wages increase due to competition for workers", "Costs will remain unchanged", "Costs will fall because workers become more productive"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: When unemployment falls, fewer workers are available, creating competition for labour. Businesses must offer higher wages to attract and retain staff, raising their production costs."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:74083960', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is a recession?", "options": ["A period when GDP is rising", "A period when unemployment is at its lowest", "A period when GDP is falling, causing income and employment to fall", "A period when consumer prices are rising"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: A recession is defined as a period when GDP is falling, which causes income to fall and unemployment to rise. Option A describes economic growth. Option D describes inflation."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:a94b3906', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Falling levels of consumer income have caused a car dealership to experience a significant reduction in retail sales. Which action should the dealership take?", "options": ["Advertise less", "Offer price reductions", "Reduce customer engagement", "Reduce its costs only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: Offering price reductions makes the cars more affordable during a period of lower consumer income, helping to maintain sales. Advertising less (A) or reducing customer engagement (C) would further harm sales."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:ae3732d8', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following statements about the impact of rising income is TRUE?", "options": ["The sales of all businesses will always increase when incomes rise", "Rising incomes often lead to an increase in sales of luxury goods", "A rise in unemployment will make all consumers worse off", "A fall in consumer income will always cause a business to sell less"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: Rising incomes often boost luxury goods sales because consumers can now afford higher-quality or non-essential items. ''Always'' in options A, C and D is incorrect — there are always exceptions (e.g. budget goods may see falls when incomes rise)."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-2-the-economic-climate:mcq:53422940', 'business', 'business:6-2-the-economic-climate', '6.2 The Economic Climate', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does GDP stand for and what does it measure?", "options": ["General Domestic Price — the average cost of goods in a country", "Gross Domestic Product — a measure of how much a country produces in a year", "Government Debt Percentage — the level of public borrowing", "Gross Disposable Pay — the average take-home wage"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: GDP (Gross Domestic Product) measures the total value of goods and services a country produces in a year. It is the key indicator of economic growth or recession."}'::jsonb)
